\section{Question 1}
\subsection{(a) Heuristic argument}
Consider the partitioned data set $X = [X_1 : X_2]$. Let $R_1^2$ be the R-squared from regressing $y$ on $X_1$ and $R_2^2$ be the R-squared from regressing y on X. \\
Show that $R_2^2 \leq R_1^2$ using a heuristic argument. That is, an informal but
logically sound explanation e.g. you may use a geometric interpretation (with
explanation or a supporting figure) or a numerical illustration.\\\\
Let $\mathcal{S}_1=\text{Col}(X_1)$ and $\mathcal{S}_2=\text{Col}(X) = \text{Col}([X_1:X_2])$ \, .\\
Since $X$ contains all columns of $X_1$ plus additional columns from $X_2$, we have
$$
\mathcal{S}_1 \subseteq \mathcal{S}_2\, .
$$
OLS can be interpreted as a projection of $y$ onto the column space of the regressors.
Regressing $y$ on $X_1$ gives the projection $\hat y_1$ onto $\mathcal{S}_1$, with residual:
$$
\hat e_1 = y - \hat y_1\, ,
\qquad
SSR_1 = \|\hat e_1\|^2 \, .
$$
Regressing $y$ on $X = [X_1:X_2]$ gives the projection $\hat y_2$ onto the larger space $\mathcal{S}_2$, with residual
$$
\hat e_2 = y - \hat y_2\, ,
\qquad
SSR_2 = \|\hat e_2\|^2\, .
$$
Since $\mathcal{S}_1 \subseteq \mathcal{S}_2$, the minimization in the second regression is taken over a larger set. Therefore, the residual sum of squares cannot increase:
$SSR_2 \leq SSR_1\, .$
Because
$$R^2 = 1 - \frac{SSR}{TSS}\, ,$$
and $TSS$ is the same in both regressions, it follows directly that
$$R_2^2 \leq R_1^2$$
Thus, adding regressors cannot decrease $R^2$.
